# Testing Conventions

## No `as any` in tests

Tests must be fully type-safe. Using `as any` hides type errors that the tests should be catching.

- Type function parameters explicitly instead of relying on inference through `as any`
- If a type doesn't fit, fix the source types -- don't silence the error in tests
- Use typed helper variables when callback parameter types can't be inferred from context

```typescript
// BAD
const configured = sdk.$configure({
  "users.$get": (request) => request.setRetry(5),
} as any);

// GOOD
const configured = sdk.$configure({
  "users.$get": (request: RequestInstance) => request.setRetry(5),
});

// GOOD -- typed helper when inference is limited
const configureFn: SocketSdkConfigurationValue = (instance) => instance.setOptions({ custom: true });
const configured = sdk.$configure({ "*": configureFn });
```
